fields.description:
If I ask {{ApplicationService}} give me all the users who are a member of the groups 'admin' or 'super-hero' and who are active and I have the following layout

Directory 1

* user { name: bob, active: false }

Directory 2

* user { name: bob, active: true }
* group { name: admin }
* membership { parent: admin, child: bob, type: group-to-user }

Then the query will return the user bob directory 2 even though he isn't the canonical user and even if bob from directory 1 was returned he doesn't match the query I specified

For example if I ask {{ApplicationService}} for users who are a member of the from 'admin' and I have the following directory layout

Directory 1

* user { name: bob, email: bob+canonical@example.com }

Directory 2

* user { name: bob, email: bob+shadowed@example.com }
* group { name: admin }
* membership { parent: admin, child: bob, type: group-to-user }

A user object with the email bob+shadowed@example.com will be returned which is incorrect

Admins should be able to set in config which IP address Crowd binds to, along with any path.  At present, only the port can be set.

We have a box running multiple services and bind all web services to {{:80}} to make things that little bit simpler for users.
At the moment we can access Atlassian services using:
{{jira.domain.com}}
{{confluence.domain.com}}
{{crowd.domain.com:8095/crowd}}
We can navigate to {{crowd.domain.com:8095}} but this always presents the Crowd 'info screen' with the buttons {{Set up Crowd}}, {{View OpenID server}}, {{View Demo Application}} and {{View OpenID client}}

We want this page to be replaced with the crowd base application sop we don't have to use {{/crowd/}} in the URL.

Jira and confluence allow this so I don't know what would prevent it being implemented in Crowd, if anything.

I use Crowd to authenticate in my project. 
